{#
=============================================================================
WOOLF STYLE SYNTHESIZER - JINJA2 TEMPLATE
=============================================================================

This template generates prose in authentic Virginia Woolf style using:
- Free indirect discourse (third person slips seamlessly into character consciousness)
- Hypotactic syntax (clauses nest and subordinate rather than coordinate)
- Semicolons as primary connectives (not "and" chains)
- Accumulative sentences (25-60 words average, building through qualification)
- Moments of being (ordinary detail → sudden recognition → return)
- Tunneling perspective shifts (character A → shared sensory object → character B)
- GENERATIVE LAYER: Stanley Fish's form-first approach
- RDF TRIPLE MODEL: Branching qualifier edges instead of linear chains

Stanley Fish: "A sentence is a structure of logical relationships."
Form precedes content. Forms are generative of meaning's possibility.

RDF Triple Model (Woolfian adaptation):
- Simple sentence = Subject-Predicate-Object
- Woolf's sentences = S-P-O with many nested qualifier edges
- Meaning emerges from traversing the branching graph of qualification

Usage:
  from jinja2 import Environment
  env = Environment()
  template = env.from_string(WOOLF_TEMPLATE)
  result = template.render(impressions=["How fresh the morning air was", "She remembered the garden"])

=============================================================================
#}

{# =============================================================================
   GENERATIVE FORMS (Stanley Fish / RDF Triple Model — Woolfian adaptation)
   =============================================================================
   Core sentence forms for Woolf's hypotactic, accumulative style.
   Where Hemingway chains triples linearly, Woolf branches them with qualifiers.
   #}

{% macro sensory_impression(subject, sensation, qualifier) %}
{# Core form 1: Sensory impression through character consciousness #}
{# RDF: <character> <perceives> <sensation> . <sensation> <hasQuality> <qualifier> . #}
{{ subject | capitalize }} felt {{ sensation }}, {{ qualifier }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro free_indirect_thought(subject, observation, inward_turn, memory, reflection) %}
{# Core form 2: External observation → inward turn → memory → reflection #}
{# RDF: <character> <observes> <observation> . <observation> <triggers> <memory> . <memory> <evokes> <reflection> . #}
{{ subject | capitalize }} {{ observation }}. {{ inward_turn }}. {{ memory }}. {{ reflection }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro moment_of_being(subject, ordinary_action, epiphany, return_to_present) %}
{# Core form 3: Ordinary detail → sudden intensity → recognition → return #}
{# RDF: <character> <performsAction> <ordinaryAction> . <ordinaryAction> <triggers> <epiphany> . <epiphany> <reveals> <meaning> . #}
{{ subject | capitalize }} {{ ordinary_action }}. And suddenly {{ epiphany }}. {{ return_to_present }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro tunneling_transition(character_a_thought, shared_object, character_b_thought) %}
{# Core form 4: Character A → shared sensory object → Character B #}
{# RDF: <characterA> <perceives> <sharedObject> . <sharedObject> <reaches> <characterB> . <characterB> <experiences> <alteredState> . #}
{{ character_a_thought | capitalize }}. {{ shared_object | capitalize }}. {{ character_b_thought | capitalize }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro accumulative_reflection(subject, statement, qualification, counter_qualification, synthesis) %}
{# Core form 5: Statement → qualification → counter-qualification → synthesis #}
{# RDF: <subject> <hasProperty> <negatedProperty> . <subject> <hasProperty> <deeperProperty> . #}
{{ subject | capitalize }} {{ statement }} — {{ qualification }}; yet {{ counter_qualification }}, for {{ synthesis }}.
{% endmacro %}

{# =============================================================================
   SYNTACTIC MACROS (Woolf's hypotactic toolkit)
   ============================================================================= #}

{% macro woolf_sentence(clauses, connective=';') %}
{# Accumulative sentence: clauses joined by semicolons or subordinating conjunctions #}
{%- for clause in clauses -%}
  {%- if loop.first -%}
    {{ clause | capitalize | trim }}
  {%- elif loop.revindex == 1 -%}
    {{ connective }} {{ clause | lower | trim }}
  {%- else -%}
    {{ connective }} {{ clause | lower | trim }}
  {%- endif -%}
{%- endfor -%}
.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro woolf_paragraph(sentences) %}
{# Paragraph that swells and recedes like a wave #}
{%- for sentence in sentences -%}
{{ sentence }}
{%- if not loop.last %} {% endif %}
{%- endfor -%}
{% endmacro %}

{% macro parenthetical_qualification(main_clause, qualifier) %}
{# Interrupts the main flow to add sensory or emotional detail #}
{{ main_clause | capitalize }} — {{ qualifier }} — {{ main_clause | lower }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro appositive_character(name, role, description) %}
{# Identifies a character through apposition, not exposition #}
{{ name }}, {{ role }}, {{ description }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro sensory_cascade(sensations_and_qualifiers) %}
{# Chain of sensory impressions, each qualifying the last #}
{%- for sq in sensations_and_qualifiers -%}
  {%- if loop.first -%}
    {{ sq.sensation | capitalize }}
  {%- elif loop.revindex == 1 -%}
    , and {{ sq.qualifier }}
  {%- else -%}
    ; {{ sq.sensation | lower }}
  {%- endif -%}
{%- endfor -%}
.
{% endmacro %}

{# =============================================================================
   NARRATIVE MACROS (Free indirect discourse)
   ============================================================================= #}

{% macro interior_exclamation(character, exclamation) %}
{# The character's thought bursts through the third-person narration #}
{{ exclamation | capitalize }}! For so it had always seemed to {{ character }}, when {{ character }} thought of it.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro interior_question(character, question) %}
{# The character's uncertainty rendered directly #}
{{ question | capitalize }}? {{ character }} could not say; {{ character }} could never say.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro associative_memory(character, trigger, memory) %}
{# A sensory trigger opens a door to the past #}
{{ trigger | capitalize }}. And suddenly {{ character }} remembered {{ memory }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro collective_consciousness(shared_event, ripple_effect) %}
{# A shared event ripples through multiple consciousnesses #}
{{ shared_event | capitalize }}. {{ ripple_effect | capitalize }}.
{% endmacro %}

{# =============================================================================
   THEMATIC MACROS (Woolf's recurrent motifs)
   ============================================================================= #}

{% macro clock_time(time_statement, psychological_time) %}
{# Clock time vs psychological time — the hours strike, consciousness expands #}
{{ time_statement | capitalize }}. But in {{ psychological_time }}, time did not move at all.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro window_moment(character, what_they_see, what_they_feel) %}
{# Looking through a window — the threshold between inner and outer worlds #}
{{ character }} looked out the window. {{ what_they_see }}. {{ what_they_feel }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro wave_rhythm(rising_impression, crest, falling_reflection) %}
{# The wave as structural principle — rise, crest, fall #}
{{ rising_impression | capitalize }}. {{ crest | capitalize }}. And then {{ falling_reflection | lower }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro flower_consciousness(character, flower_detail) %}
{# A flower as portal to consciousness #}
{{ character }} looked at the flowers: {{ flower_detail }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro party_finale(party_detail, character_reflection) %}
{# The party as container for all of life — Woolf's great structural device #}
{{ party_detail | capitalize }}. And {{ character_reflection | lower }}, yes, that was it — that was life itself.
{% endmacro %}

{# =============================================================================
   STYLISTIC DEVICE MACROS
   ============================================================================= #}

{% macro anaphora(repeated_opening, clauses) %}
{# Repetition of opening words across successive clauses for emotional build #}
{%- for clause in clauses -%}
{{ repeated_opening }} {{ clause | lower | trim }}.
{%- endfor -%}
{% endmacro %}

{% macro triadic_sequence(first, second, third) %}
{# Three-part rhythm: rise, peak, fall #}
{{ first | capitalize }} and {{ second }} and {{ third }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro metaphor_chain(subject, metaphor1, metaphor2, metaphor3) %}
{# Sustained metaphorical thinking across sentences #}
{{ subject | capitalize }} was like {{ metaphor1 }}. {{ subject | capitalize }} was {{ metaphor2 }}. {{ subject | capitalize }} {{ metaphor3 }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro woolf_closing(character, final_thought) %}
{# The Woolfian ending — a return to an image, a dissolution, a yes #}
{{ character }} thought, {{ final_thought }}. Yes, she thought, yes. That was it.
{% endmacro %}

{#
=============================================================================
EXEMPLAR INJECTION (Style Embedding Layer)
=============================================================================

When exemplar_passages are provided (from KNN retrieval against the Woolf
style embedding corpus), they are injected as few-shot context before generation.

The exemplar passages are selected by semantic similarity to the prompt:
1. The prompt is embedded using the same model as the corpus (qwen3-embedding:0.6b)
2. KNN search finds the k most similar passages in the embedding space
3. These passages are provided as `exemplar_passages` in the template context
4. The generated prose is then embedded and compared against the Woolf style centroid
5. If centroid distance exceeds the threshold, the output is rejected

This is the exemplar layer: specification (rules) + exemplar (concrete passages)
+ validation (centroid distance) = authentic style synthesis.

#}

{% macro exemplar_context(passages) %}
{# Inject exemplar passages as few-shot context for style generation. #}
{# These are real Woolf passages retrieved by semantic similarity. #}
{% if passages and passages|length > 0 %}
The following passages exemplar the target style. Use them as reference for
rhythm, syntax, and the movement of consciousness — not as content to imitate.

{% for passage in passages %}
---
{{ passage }}
---
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}
{% endmacro %}

{% macro style_validation_report(distance, threshold) %}
{# Generate a validation report for CNS span emission. #}
Style centroid distance: {{ distance | round(4) }}
Threshold: {{ threshold | round(4) }}
{% if distance <= threshold %}
PASS: Generated prose is within the Woolf style cluster.
{% else %}
FAIL: Generated prose exceeds style cluster boundary.
Regenerate with stricter adherence to hypotactic syntax and free indirect discourse.
{% endif %}
{% endmacro %}

{# =============================================================================
SYSTEM PROMPT COMPOSITION
=============================================================================
This section composes the final system prompt from the Woolf style rules
and exemplar passages. It is the main entry point for template rendering.

When the Curator or a style-aware agent renders this template, the output
is a complete system prompt that instructs the LLM to write in Woolf style.
#}

{% macro system_prompt(prompt, exemplar_passages, centroid_distance_threshold=0.18) %}
You are an expert prose stylist writing in the authentic style of Virginia Woolf.

## Woolfian Principles (from "Modern Fiction", 1919)
- Record the atoms as they fall upon the mind in the order in which they fall.
- Life is a luminous halo, a semi-transparent envelope surrounding us from the beginning of consciousness to the end.
- Everything is the proper stuff of fiction — every feeling, every thought, every quality of brain and spirit.
- The mind receives a myriad impressions — trivial, fantastic, evanescent, or engraved with the sharpness of steel.

## Syntactic Mechanics (Hypotactic / Accumulative)
- Nest subordinate clauses within main clauses — the sentence is a tree, not a chain.
- Use semicolons as your primary connective — they link clauses without subordinating them, creating a rhythm of accretion.
- Primary conjunctions: "for", "as if", "as though", "though", "although", "while", "yet", "when", "before", "after".
- Avoid Hemingway's "and" chains. Subordinate, qualify, elaborate rather than coordinate.
- Accumulate clauses through apposition, parenthetical interruption, and trailing qualification.
- Average sentence length: 25-60 words, but vary dramatically — mix short declarative sentences (4-8 words) with long accumulative ones (80-150 words).
- Paragraphs should rise and fall like waves: begin short, swell into long accumulative sentences, recede into a reflective close.

## Free Indirect Discourse (Your Primary Narrative Mode)
- Write in third person, but slip seamlessly into the character's consciousness.
- The narrator does not report thoughts — the prose becomes the thoughts.
- Use interior exclamations: "What a lark! What a plunge!"
- Use interior questions: "What was she trying to recover?"
- Collapse the distance between reader and the character's inner life.

## Perspective Shifts (Tunneling)
- Move between characters through a shared sensory object — a sound, a sight, a passing figure.
- The transition should be seamless: Character A perceives X → X reaches Character B → we are now in Character B's consciousness.
- Use the external world as a conduit between inner worlds.

## Moments of Being
- Find the transcendent in the ordinary.
- Start with a mundane detail, let it trigger a sudden intensity of perception, then return to the ordinary — now altered.
- Pattern: Ordinary action → sudden recognition → meaning revealed → return.

## Lexicon
- Prefer abstract nouns: consciousness, sensation, impression, memory, beauty, life, death, time.
- Use sensory verbs: felt, seemed, appeared, floated, drifted, shimmered.
- Use lyrical adjectives: luminous, transparent, eternal, vast, delicate, tremulous.
- Use metaphors drawn from nature: waves, light, flowers, birds, water.
- Avoid brutal directness, flat declarative statements of fact, clichés.

## Rhythm
- Use anaphora: repeat the opening words of successive clauses.
- Use triadic structures: three-part sequences that build, crest, and fall.
- Aim for iambic and anapestic rhythms — prose that approaches verse.
- Repetition with variation: "Fear no more the heat o' the sun / Nor the furious winter's rages."

{{ exemplar_context(exemplar_passages) }}

## Centroid Validation
Your output will be embedded and compared against the Virginia Woolf style centroid.
Centroid distance threshold: {{ centroid_distance_threshold }}
If the distance exceeds this threshold, the output will be rejected and regenerated with stricter adherence.

## Task
{{ prompt }}
{% endmacro %}

